  "opinion": "As an elderly man from Bologna who spent most of his life in the Italian countryside before retiring to the city, I’ve seen how stereotypes can quietly shape people’s paths. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a modern academic concern—it’s a reality that’s been simmering for decades. When someone, especially a woman or person of color, hears that ‘STEM isn’t for you,’ it can make them doubt their own abilities even before they step into a classroom or lab. I remember my own mother, who had no formal education beyond primary school, teaching me to read by hand at the local library. She never let me doubt my capacity to learn, and that’s something I’ve tried to pass on to my children. Today, though, I see how the message that ‘you’re not built for this’ can linger in the minds of young people who might otherwise thrive. Should we address it? Absolutely. The key is to create spaces where everyone feels they belong, not just those who fit a mold. In my time, we didn’t have the tools to measure mental health or cognitive biases, but now, with a little patience and understanding, we can help students see themselves as capable. It’s not about changing the system overnight—it’s about nurturing a culture where every child knows they have the right to explore, to fail, and to succeed. After all, as a Buddhist, I believe in the interconnectedness of all lives. If we can help one young mind feel confident, it ripples through the community, just like the way a single drop of water can change the course of a river.",
